[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In machine learning, **diffusion models**, also known as **diffusion-based generative models** or **score-based generative models**, are a class of latent variable generative models.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] A diffusion model consists of two major components: the forward diffusion process, and the reverse sampling process.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The goal of diffusion models is to learn a diffusion process for a given dataset, such that the process can generate new elements that are distributed similarly as the original dataset.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] A diffusion model models data as generated by a diffusion process, whereby a new datum performs a random walk with drift through the space of all possible data.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] A trained diffusion model can be sampled in many ways, with different efficiency and quality.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] There are various equivalent formalisms, including Markov chains, denoising diffusion probabilistic models, noise conditioned score networks, and stochastic differential equations.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] They are typically trained using variational inference.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The model responsible for denoising is typically called its "backbone".
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The backbone may be of any kind, but they are typically U-nets or transformers.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] As of 2024, diffusion models are mainly used for computer vision tasks, including image denoising, inpainting, super-resolution, image generation, and video generation.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] These typically involve training a neural network to sequentially denoise images blurred with Gaussian noise.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The model is trained to reverse the process of adding noise to an image.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] After training to convergence, it can be used for image generation by starting with an image composed of random noise, and applying the network iteratively to denoise the image.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Diffusion-based image generators have seen widespread commercial interest, such as Stable Diffusion and DALL-E.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] These models typically combine diffusion models with other models, such as text-encoders and cross-attention modules to allow text-conditioned generation.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Other than computer vision, diffusion models have also found applications in natural language processing such as text generation and summarization, sound generation, and reinforcement learning.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Diffusion models were introduced in 2015 as a method to train a model that can sample from a highly complex probability distribution.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] They used techniques from non-equilibrium thermodynamics, especially diffusion.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Consider, for example, how one might model the distribution of all naturally occurring photos.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] A model that can approximately undo the diffusion can then be used to sample from the original distribution.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] This is studied in "non-equilibrium" thermodynamics, as the starting distribution is not in equilibrium, unlike the final distribution.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] This is just the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution of particles in a potential well $V(x)={\frac {1}{2}}\|x\|^{2}$ at temperature 1.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The initial distribution, being very much out of equilibrium, would diffuse towards the equilibrium distribution, making biased random steps that are a sum of pure randomness (like a Brownian walker) and gradient descent down the potential well.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The randomness is necessary: if the particles were to undergo only gradient descent, then they will all fall to the origin, collapsing the distribution.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The 2020 paper proposed the Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Model (DDPM), which improves upon the previous method by variational inference.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] To present the model, some notation is required.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The values of $\beta _{t}$ are chosen such that for any starting distribution of $x_{0}$ , if it has finite second moment, then $\lim _{t\to \infty }x_{t}|x_{0}$ converges to ${\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In particular, we note that $x_{1:T}|x_{0}$ is a Gaussian process, which affords us considerable freedom in reparameterization.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] That is, after a long enough diffusion process, we end up with some $x_{T}$ that is very close to ${\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ , with all traces of the original $x_{0}\sim q$ gone.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] We also know that these are independent.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] There are 5 variables ${\textstyle x_{0},x_{t-1},x_{t},z,z'}$ and two linear equations.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The two sources of randomness are ${\textstyle z,z'}$ , which can be reparameterized by rotation, since the IID Gaussian distribution is rotationally symmetric.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] By plugging in the equations, we can solve for the first reparameterization: $x_{t}={\sqrt {{\bar {\alpha }}_{t}}}x_{0}+\underbrace {{\sqrt {\alpha _{t}-{\bar {\alpha }}_{t}}}z+{\sqrt {1-\alpha _{t}}}z'} _{=\sigma _{t}z''}$ where ${\textstyle z''}$ is a Gaussian with mean zero and variance one.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The key idea of DDPM is to use a neural network parametrized by $\theta$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] To do that, we use maximum likelihood estimation with variational inference.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] This allows us to perform variational inference.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Define the loss function $L(\theta ):=-E_{x_{0:T}\sim q}[\ln p_{\theta }(x_{0:T})-\ln q(x_{1:T}|x_{0})]$ and now the goal is to minimize the loss by stochastic gradient descent.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Now we see that estimating $x_{0}$ is equivalent to estimating z .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The DDPM paper suggested not learning it (since it resulted in "unstable training and poorer sample quality"), but fixing it at some value $\Sigma _{\theta }(x_{t},t)=\zeta _{t}^{2}I$ , where either $\zeta _{t}^{2}=\beta _{t}{\text{ or }}{\tilde {\sigma }}_{t}^{2}$ yielded similar performance.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The paper noted empirically that an even simpler loss function $L_{simple,t}=E_{x_{0}\sim q;z\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,I)}\left[\left\|\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t)-z\right\|^{2}\right]$ resulted in better models.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Score-based generative model is another formulation of diffusion modelling.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] They are also called noise conditional score network (NCSN) or score-matching with Langevin dynamics (SMLD).
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Consider the problem of image generation.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Let x represent an image, and let $q(x)$ be the probability distribution over all possible images.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] If we have $q(x)$ itself, then we can say for certain how likely a certain image is.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] However, this is intractable in general.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Most often, we are uninterested in knowing the absolute probability of a certain image.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Instead, we are usually only interested in knowing how likely a certain image is compared to its immediate neighbors — e.g. how much more likely is an image of cat compared to some small variants of it?
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Is it more likely if the image contains two whiskers, or three, or with some Gaussian noise added?
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Consequently, we are actually quite uninterested in $q(x)$ itself, but rather, $\nabla _{x}\ln q(x)$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Let the score function be $s(x):=\nabla _{x}\ln q(x)$ ; then consider what we can do with $s(x)$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] As it turns out, $s(x)$ allows us to sample from $q(x)$ using thermodynamics.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Specifically, if we have a potential energy function $U(x)=-\ln q(x)$ , and a lot of particles in the potential well, then the distribution at thermodynamic equilibrium is the Boltzmann distribution $q_{U}(x)\propto e^{-U(x)/k_{B}T}=q(x)^{1/k_{B}T}$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] At temperature $k_{B}T=1$ , the Boltzmann distribution is exactly $q(x)$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] So no matter what distribution $x_{0}$ has, the distribution of $x_{t}$ converges in distribution to q as $t\to \infty$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Given a density q , we wish to learn a score function approximation $f_{\theta }\approx \nabla \ln q$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] This is **score matching***.* Typically, score matching is formalized as minimizing **Fisher divergence** function $E_{q}[\|f_{\theta }(x)-\nabla \ln q(x)\|^{2}]$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] By expanding the integral, and performing an integration by parts, $E_{q}[\|f_{\theta }(x)-\nabla \ln q(x)\|^{2}]=E_{q}[\|f_{\theta }\|^{2}+2\nabla \cdot f_{\theta }]+C$ giving us a loss function, also known as the Hyvärinen scoring rule, that can be minimized by stochastic gradient descent.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Suppose we need to model the distribution of images, and we want $x_{0}\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ , a white-noise image.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Now, most white-noise images do not look like real images, so $q(x_{0})\approx 0$ for large swaths of $x_{0}\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] This presents a problem for learning the score function, because if there are no samples around a certain point, then we can't learn the score function at that point.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] If we do not know the score function $\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln q(x_{t})$ at that point, then we cannot impose the time-evolution equation on a particle: $dx_{t}=\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln q(x_{t})dt+dW_{t}$ To deal with this problem, we perform annealing.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] If q is too different from a white-noise distribution, then progressively add noise until it is indistinguishable from one.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] That is, we perform a forward diffusion, then learn the score function, then use the score function to perform a backward diffusion.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Now, the equation is exactly a special case of the overdamped Langevin equation $dx_{t}=-{\frac {D}{k_{B}T}}(\nabla _{x}U)dt+{\sqrt {2D}}dW_{t}$ where D is diffusion tensor, T is temperature, and U is potential energy field.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] This explains why the phrase "Langevin dynamics" is sometimes used in diffusion models.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Now the above equation is for the stochastic motion of a single particle.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Suppose we have a cloud of particles distributed according to q at time $t=0$ , then after a long time, the cloud of particles would settle into the stable distribution of ${\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Let $\rho _{t}$ be the density of the cloud of particles at time t , then we have $\rho _{0}=q;\quad \rho _{T}\approx {\mathcal {N}}(0,I)$ and the goal is to somehow reverse the process, so that we can start at the end and diffuse back to the beginning.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] By Fokker-Planck equation, the density of the cloud evolves according to $\partial _{t}\ln \rho _{t}={\frac {1}{2}}\beta (t)\left(n+(x+\nabla \ln \rho _{t})\cdot \nabla \ln \rho _{t}+\Delta \ln \rho _{t}\right)$ where n is the dimension of space, and $\Delta$ is the Laplace operator.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] If we have solved $\rho _{t}$ for time $t\in [0,T]$ , then we can exactly reverse the evolution of the cloud.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] then by plugging into the Fokker-Planck equation, we find that $\partial _{t}\rho _{T-t}=\partial _{t}\nu _{t}$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Thus this cloud of points is the original cloud, evolving backwards.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] That is, we can quickly sample $x_{t}\sim \rho _{t}$ for any $t\geq 0$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] DDPM and score-based generative models are equivalent.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] This means that a network trained using DDPM can be used as a NCSN, and vice versa.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Thus, given a good score-based network, its predicted score is a good prediction of the noise (after scaling by $\sigma _{t}$ ), and thus can be used for denoising.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In DDPM, the sequence of numbers $0=\sigma _{0}<\sigma _{1}<\cdots <\sigma _{T}<1$ is called a (discrete time) **noise schedule**.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In general, consider a strictly increasing monotonic function $\sigma$ of type $\mathbb {R} \to (0,1)$ , such as the sigmoid function.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In that case, a noise schedule is a sequence of real numbers $\lambda _{1}<\lambda _{2}<\cdots <\lambda _{T}$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In order to use arbitrary noise schedules, instead of training a noise prediction model $\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t)$ , one trains $\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},\sigma _{t})$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Similarly, for the noise conditional score network, instead of training $f_{\theta }(x_{t},t)$ , one trains $f_{\theta }(x_{t},\sigma _{t})$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The original DDPM method for generating images is slow, since the forward diffusion process usually takes $T\sim 1000$ to make the distribution of $x_{T}$ to appear close to Gaussian.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] However this means the backward diffusion process also take 1000 steps.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Unlike the forward diffusion process, which can skip steps as $x_{t}|x_{0}$ is Gaussian for all $t\geq 1$ , the backward diffusion process does not allow skipping steps.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Attempting to directly sample $x_{t-2}|x_{t}$ would require us to marginalize out $x_{t-1}$ , which is generally intractable.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] DDIM is a method to take any model trained on DDPM loss, and use it to sample with some steps skipped, sacrificing an adjustable amount of quality.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] If we generate the Markovian chain case in DDPM to non-Markovian case, DDIM corresponds to the case that the reverse process has variance equals to 0.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In other words, the reverse process (and also the forward process) is deterministic.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] When using fewer sampling steps, DDIM outperforms DDPM.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In detail, the DDIM sampling method is as follows.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] If all $\sigma _{s}'=0$ , then the backward process becomes deterministic, and this special case of DDIM is also called "DDIM".
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The original paper noted that when the process is deterministic, samples generated with only 20 steps are already very similar to ones generated with 1000 steps on the high-level.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The original paper recommended defining a single "eta value" $\eta \in [0,1]$ , such that $\sigma _{s}'=\eta {\tilde {\sigma }}_{s}$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] When $\eta =1$ , this is the original DDPM.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] When $\eta =0$ , this is the fully deterministic DDIM.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] For intermediate values, the process interpolates between them.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] By the equivalence, the DDIM algorithm also applies for score-based diffusion models.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Since the diffusion model is a general method for modelling probability distributions, if one wants to model a distribution over images, one can first encode the images into a lower-dimensional space by an encoder, then use a diffusion model to model the distribution over encoded images.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Then to generate an image, one can sample from the diffusion model, then use a decoder to decode it into an image.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The encoder-decoder pair is most often a variational autoencoder (VAE).
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] proposed various architectural improvements.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] For example, they proposed log-space interpolation during backward sampling.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] This parameterization was found to improve performance, as the model can be trained to reach total noise (i.e. $\phi _{t}=90^{\circ }$ ) and then reverse it, whereas the standard parameterization never reaches total noise since ${\sqrt {{\bar {\alpha }}_{t}}}>0$ is always true.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Classifier guidance was proposed in 2021 to improve class-conditional generation by using a classifier.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The original publication used CLIP text encoders to improve text-conditional image generation.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Suppose we wish to sample not from the entire distribution of images, but conditional on the image description.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] We don't want to sample a generic image, but an image that fits the description "black cat with red eyes".
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Generally, we want to sample from the distribution $p(x|y)$ , where x ranges over images, and y ranges over classes of images (a description "black cat with red eyes" is just a very detailed class, and a class "cat" is just a very vague description).
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Taking the perspective of the noisy channel model, we can understand the process as follows: To generate an image x conditional on description y , we imagine that the requester really had in mind an image x , but the image is passed through a noisy channel and came out garbled, as y .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Image generation is then nothing but inferring which x the requester had in mind.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In other words, conditional image generation is simply "translating from a textual language into a pictorial language".
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Then, as in noisy-channel model, we use Bayes theorem to get $p(x|y)\propto p(y|x)p(x)$ in other words, if we have a good model of the space of all images, and a good image-to-class translator, we get a class-to-image translator "for free".
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] During the diffusion process, we need to condition on the time, giving $\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln p(x_{t}|y,t)=\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln p(y|x_{t},t)+\nabla _{x_{t}}\ln p(x_{t}|t)$ Although, usually the classifier model does not depend on time, in which case $p(y|x_{t},t)=p(y|x_{t})$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The classifier-guided diffusion model samples from $p(x|y)$ , which is concentrated around the maximum a posteriori estimate $\arg \max _{x}p(x|y)$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] If we want to force the model to move towards the maximum likelihood estimate $\arg \max _{x}p(y|x)$ , we can use $p_{\gamma }(x|y)\propto p(y|x)^{\gamma }p(x)$ where $\gamma >0$ is interpretable as *inverse temperature*.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In the context of diffusion models, it is usually called the **guidance scale**.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] A high $\gamma$ would force the model to sample from a distribution concentrated around $\arg \max _{x}p(y|x)$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] This sometimes improves quality of generated images.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Note that for CFG, the diffusion model cannot be merely a generative model of the entire data distribution $\nabla _{x}\ln p(x)$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] It must be a conditional generative model $\nabla _{x}\ln p(x|y)$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] For example, in stable diffusion, the diffusion backbone takes as input both a noisy model $x_{t}$ , a time t , and a conditioning vector y (such as a vector encoding a text prompt), and produces a noise prediction $\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},y,t)$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Also, if the unconditional generation $\epsilon _{\text{uncond}}\leftarrow \epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t)$ is replaced by $\epsilon _{\text{neg cond}}\leftarrow \epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t,c')$ , then it results in negative prompting, which pushes the generation away from $c'$ condition.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Given a diffusion model, one may regard it either as a continuous process, and sample from it by integrating a SDE, or one can regard it as a discrete process, and sample from it by iterating the discrete steps.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The choice of the "**noise schedule**" $\beta _{t}$ can also affect the quality of samples.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] A noise schedule is a function that sends a natural number to a noise level: $t\mapsto \beta _{t},\quad t\in \{1,2,\dots \},\beta \in (0,1)$ A noise schedule is more often specified by a map $t\mapsto \sigma _{t}$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In the DDPM perspective, one can use the DDPM itself (with noise), or DDIM (with adjustable amount of noise).
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The case where one adds noise is sometimes called ancestral sampling.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] One can interpolate between noise and no noise.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The amount of noise is denoted $\eta$ ("eta value") in the DDIM paper, with $\eta =0$ denoting no noise (as in *deterministic* DDIM), and $\eta =1$ denoting full noise (as in DDPM).
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In the perspective of SDE, one can use any of the numerical integration methods, such as Euler–Maruyama method, Heun's method, linear multistep methods, etc.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Just as in the discrete case, one can add an adjustable amount of noise during the integration.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] A survey and comparison of samplers in the context of image generation is in.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Notable variants include Poisson flow generative model, consistency model, critically damped Langevin diffusion, GenPhys, cold diffusion, etc.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The probability path is in fact defined implicitly by the score function $\nabla \ln p_{t}$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In denoising diffusion models, the forward process adds noise, and the backward process removes noise.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Both the forward and backward processes are SDEs, though the forward process is integrable in closed-form, so it can be done at no computational cost.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The backward process is not integrable in closed-form, so it must be integrated step-by-step by standard SDE solvers, which can be very expensive.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The probability path in diffusions model is defined through an Itô process and one can retrieve the deterministic process by using the Probability ODE flow formulation.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In flow-based diffusion models, the forward process is a deterministic flow along a time-dependent vector field, and the backward process is also a deterministic flow along the same vector field, but going backwards.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] If the vector field is well-behaved, the ODE will also be well-behaved.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The solution $\phi _{t}$ of the above ODE define a probability path $p_{t}=[\phi _{t}]_{\#}\pi _{0}$ by the pushforward measure operator.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The idea of **optimal transport flow** is to construct a probability path minimizing the Wasserstein metric.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The idea of **rectified flow** is to learn a flow model such that the velocity is nearly constant along each flow path.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] This is beneficial, because we can integrate along such a vector field with very few steps.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] For example, if an ODE ${\dot {\phi _{t}}}(x)=v_{t}(\phi _{t}(x))$ follows perfectly straight paths, it simplifies to $\phi _{t}(x)=x_{0}+t\cdot v_{0}(x_{0})$ , allowing for exact solutions in one step.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In practice, we cannot reach such perfection, but when the flow field is nearly so, we can take a few large steps instead of many little steps.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] The general idea is to start with two distributions $\pi _{0}$ and $\pi _{1}$ , then construct a flow field $\phi ^{0}=\{\phi _{t}:t\in [0,1]\}$ from it, then repeatedly apply a "reflow" operation to obtain successive flow fields $\phi ^{1},\phi ^{2},\dots$ , each straighter than the previous one.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] When the flow field is straight enough for the application, we stop.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] In rectified flow, by injecting strong priors that intermediate trajectories are straight, it can achieve both theoretical relevance for optimal transport and computational efficiency, as ODEs with straight paths can be simulated precisely without time discretization.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Specifically, rectified flow seeks to match an ODE with the marginal distributions of the **linear interpolation** between points from distributions $\pi _{0}$ and $\pi _{1}$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] This process ensures that the trajectories closely mirror the density map of $x_{t}$ trajectories but *reroute* at intersections to ensure causality.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] A distinctive aspect of rectified flow is its capability for "**reflow**", which straightens the trajectory of ODE paths.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] This "reflow" process not only reduces transport costs but also straightens the paths of rectified flows, making $\phi ^{k}$ paths straighter with increasing k .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] Rectified flow includes a nonlinear extension where linear interpolation $x_{t}$ is replaced with any time-differentiable curve that connects $x_{0}$ and $x_{1}$ , given by $x_{t}=\alpha _{t}x_{1}+\beta _{t}x_{0}$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] This framework encompasses DDIM and probability flow ODEs as special cases, with particular choices of $\alpha _{t}$ and $\beta _{t}$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] However, in the case where the path of $x_{t}$ is not straight, the reflow process no longer ensures a reduction in convex transport costs, and also no longer straighten the paths of $\phi _{t}$ .
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] These linear flow formulations were independently discovered and adapted from a different perspective for supervised inverse problems.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] For example, Inversion by Direct Iteration (InDI) formulates image restoration by learning a residual flow ODE that iteratively reverses a linear interpolation between a degraded input and a high-quality target to avoid regression-to-the-mean.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p01] InDI is effective for a variety of image restoration tasks.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] For generating images by DDPM, we need a neural network that takes a time t and a noisy image $x_{t}$ , and predicts a noise $\epsilon _{\theta }(x_{t},t)$ from it.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Since predicting the noise is the same as predicting the denoised image, then subtracting it from $x_{t}$ , denoising architectures tend to work well.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] For example, the U-Net, which was found to be good for denoising images, is often used for denoising diffusion models that generate images.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] For DDPM, the underlying architecture ("backbone") does not have to be a U-Net.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] It just has to predict the noise somehow.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] For example, the diffusion transformer (DiT) uses a Transformer to predict the mean and diagonal covariance of the noise, given the textual conditioning and the partially denoised image.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] It is the same as standard U-Net-based denoising diffusion model, with a Transformer replacing the U-Net.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Mixture of experts-Transformer can also be applied.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] DDPM can be used to model general data distributions, not just natural-looking images.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] For example, Human Motion Diffusion models human motion trajectory by DDPM.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Each human motion trajectory is a sequence of poses, represented by either joint rotations or positions.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] It uses a Transformer network to generate a less noisy trajectory out of a noisy one.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The base diffusion model can only generate unconditionally from the whole distribution.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] For example, a diffusion model learned on ImageNet would generate images that look like a random image from ImageNet.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] To generate images from just one category, one would need to impose the condition, and then sample from the conditional distribution.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Whatever condition one wants to impose, one needs to first convert the conditioning into a vector of floating point numbers, then feed it into the underlying diffusion model neural network.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] However, one has freedom in choosing how to convert the conditioning into a vector.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Stable Diffusion, for example, imposes conditioning in the form of cross-attention mechanism, where the query is an intermediate representation of the image in the U-Net, and both key and value are the conditioning vectors.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The conditioning can be selectively applied to only parts of an image, and new kinds of conditionings can be finetuned upon the base model, as used in ControlNet.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] As a particularly simple example, consider image inpainting.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The conditions are ${\tilde {x}}$ , the reference image, and m , the inpainting mask.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Another application of cross-attention mechanism is prompt-to-prompt image editing.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Conditioning is not limited to just generating images from a specific category, or according to a specific caption (as in text-to-image).
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] For example, demonstrated generating human motion, conditioned on an audio clip of human walking (allowing syncing motion to a soundtrack), or video of human running, or a text description of human motion, etc.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] For how conditional diffusion models are mathematically formulated, see a methodological summary in.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] As generating an image takes a long time, one can try to generate a small image by a base diffusion model, then upscale it by other models.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Upscaling can be done by GAN, Transformer, or signal processing methods like Lanczos resampling.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Diffusion models themselves can be used to perform upscaling.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Cascading diffusion model stacks multiple diffusion models one after another, in the style of Progressive GAN.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The lowest level is a standard diffusion model that generate 32x32 image, then the image would be upscaled by a diffusion model specifically trained for upscaling, and the process repeats.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] This section collects some notable diffusion models, and briefly describes their architecture.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The DALL-E series by OpenAI are text-conditional diffusion models of images.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The first version of DALL-E (2021) is not actually a diffusion model.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Instead, it uses a Transformer architecture that autoregressively generates a sequence of tokens, which is then converted to an image by the decoder of a discrete VAE.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Released with DALL-E was the CLIP classifier, which was used by DALL-E to rank generated images according to how close the image fits the text.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] GLIDE (2022–03) is a 3.5-billion diffusion model, and a small version was released publicly.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] DALL-E 2 is a 3.5-billion cascaded diffusion model that generates images from text by "inverting the CLIP image encoder", the technique which they termed "unCLIP".
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The unCLIP method contains 4 models: a CLIP image encoder, a CLIP text encoder, an image decoder, and a "prior" model (which can be a diffusion model, or an autoregressive model).
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] During training, the prior model is trained to convert CLIP image encodings to CLIP text encodings.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The image decoder is trained to convert CLIP image encodings back to images.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] During inference, a text is converted by the CLIP text encoder to a vector, then it is converted by the prior model to an image encoding, then it is converted by the image decoder to an image.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Sora (2024–02) is a diffusion Transformer model (DiT).
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] LTX is a family of open source artificial intelligence video foundation models developed by Lightricks, first released in November 2024.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The latest models, LTX-2, create videos based on user prompts, conditioned on text, images, video or audio - and capable of generating audio and visual in a unified way.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] They were preceded by LTX Video, which was released in 2024 as the company's first text-to-video model.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Stable Diffusion (2022–08), released by Stability AI, consists of a denoising latent diffusion model (860 million parameters), a VAE, and a text encoder.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The denoising network is a U-Net, with cross-attention blocks to allow for conditional image generation.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Stable Diffusion 3 (2024–03) changed the latent diffusion model from the UNet to a Transformer model, and so it is a DiT.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Stable Video 4D (2024–07) is a latent diffusion model for videos of 3D objects.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Imagen (2022) uses a T5-XXL language model to encode the input text into an embedding vector.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] It is a cascaded diffusion model with three sub-models.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The first step denoises a white noise to a 64×64 image, conditional on the embedding vector of the text.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The second step upscales the image by 64×64→256×256, conditional on embedding.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The three denoising networks are all U-Nets.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Muse (2023–01) is not a diffusion model, but an encoder-only Transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Imagen 2 (2023–12) is also diffusion-based.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] It can generate images based on a prompt that mixes images and text.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Veo (2024) generates videos by latent diffusion.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] The diffusion is conditioned on a vector that encodes both a text prompt and an image prompt.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Make-A-Video (2022) is a text-to-video diffusion model.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] CM3leon (2023) is not a diffusion model, but an autoregressive causally masked Transformer, with mostly the same architecture as LLaMa-2.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Transfusion (2024) is a Transformer that combines autoregressive text generation and denoising diffusion.
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Specifically, it generates text autoregressively (with causal masking), and generates images by denoising multiple times over image tokens (with all-to-all attention).
[src:stable-diffusion/diffusion-model-p02] Movie Gen (2024) is a series of Diffusion Transformers operating on latent space and by flow matching.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The prevalence of generative AI tools has increased significantly since the AI boom in the 2020s.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] This boom was made possible by improvements in deep neural networks, particularly large language models (LLMs), which are based on the transformer architecture.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI applications include chatbots such as ChatGPT, Claude, Copilot, DeepSeek, Doubao, Google Gemini, Grok and Qwen; text-to-image models such as DALL-E, Firefly, Stable Diffusion, and Midjourney; and text-to-video models such as Veo, LTX and Sora.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies in a variety of sectors have used generative AI, including those in software development, healthcare, finance, entertainment, customer service, sales and marketing, art, writing, and product design.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI has been used for cybercrime, and to deceive and manipulate people through fake news and deepfakes.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI models have been trained on copyrighted works without the rightholders' permission.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many generative AI systems use large-scale data centers, whose environmental impacts include electronic waste, consumption of fresh water for cooling, and high energy consumption that is estimated to be growing steadily.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The origins of algorithmically generated media can be traced to the development of the Markov chain, which has been used to model natural language since the early 20th century.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Russian mathematician Andrey Markov introduced the concept in 1906, including an analysis of vowel and consonant patterns in *Eugene Onegin*.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Once trained on a text corpus, a Markov chain can generate probabilistic text.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] By the early 1970s, artists began using computers to extend generative techniques beyond Markov models.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Harold Cohen developed and exhibited works produced by AARON, a pioneering computer program designed to autonomously create paintings.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The terms generative AI planning or generative planning were used in the 1980s and 1990s to refer to AI planning systems, especially computer-aided process planning, used to generate sequences of actions to reach a specified goal.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI planning systems used symbolic AI methods such as state space search and constraint satisfaction and were a "relatively mature" technology by the early 1990s.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] They were used to generate crisis action plans for military use, process plans for manufacturing and decision plans such as in prototype autonomous spacecraft.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Machine learning uses both discriminative models and generative models to predict or generate data.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Beginning in the late 2000s and early 2010s, advances in deep learning led to major improvements in image classification, speech recognition, and natural language processing.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Neural networks in this period were typically trained as discriminative models due to the relative difficulty of training generative models.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2014, the introduction of models such as the variational autoencoder (VAE) and generative adversarial network (GAN) enabled effective deep generative modeling of complex data such as images.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2017, the Transformer architecture enabled further advances in generative modeling compared to earlier long short-term memory (LSTM) networks.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] This led to the development of generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) models, beginning with GPT-1 in 2018.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In March 2020, the release of 15.ai, a free web application created by an anonymous MIT researcher that could generate convincing character voices using minimal training data, was one of the earliest publicly available uses for generative AI.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The platform is credited as the first mainstream service for audio deepfakes.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2021, DALL-E, a closed-source transformer-based generative model developed by OpenAI, drew widespread attention to text-to-image generation.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Other projects, including open-source approaches such as VQGAN+CLIP and DALL·E Mini (later renamed Craiyon), made similar systems more accessible to the public.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Dream by Wombo was released at the end of 2021, followed by the releases of Midjourney and Stable Diffusion in 2022.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In November 2022, ChatGPT was released to the public.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] By 2023, it popularized generative AI for general-purpose text-based tasks.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In a 2024 survey by marketing research firm Ipsos, Asia–Pacific countries were significantly more optimistic than Western societies about generative AI and show higher adoption rates.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Despite expressing concerns about privacy and the pace of change, 68% of Asia-Pacific respondents believed that AI was having a positive impact on the world, compared to 57% globally.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to a survey by SAS and Coleman Parkes Research, as of 2023, 83% of Chinese respondents were using the technology, exceeding both the global average of 54% and the U.S. rate of 65%.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] A UN report indicated that Chinese entities filed over 38,000 generative AI patents from 2014 to 2023, more than any other country.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2024 survey by the Just So Soul social media app reported that 18% of respondents born after 2000 used generative AI "almost every day", and that over 60% of respondents like or love AI-generated content (AIGC), while less than 3% dislike or hate it.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative artificial intelligence has been applied across multiple industries for content creation and automation.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In healthcare, generative models are used for drug discovery and the generation of synthetic medical data to train diagnostic systems.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In finance, they are used for report drafting, data generation, and customer service automation.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Media and entertainment industries use generative systems for tasks such as music composition, script development, and image or video generation.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Researchers and policymakers have raised concerns regarding accuracy, misuse, and impacts on academic and professional work.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Large language models (LLMs) are trained on tokenized text from large corpora and are capable of natural language processing, machine translation, and natural language generation.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] LLMs can be used as foundation models for a variety of downstream tasks.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] They can also be trained on source code to generate programs from prompts.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2016, DeepMind's WaveNet demonstrated that deep neural networks can generate raw audio waveforms.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] This enabled more realistic speech synthesis compared to earlier approaches.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Subsequent systems such as Tacotron 2 demonstrated end-to-end neural text-to-speech generation.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to create visual art.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Such systems are trained on image–text pairs.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Examples include Stable Diffusion, DALL-E, and Midjourney.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to produce photorealistic videos.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Systems such as Runway have demonstrated text-to-video generation capabilities.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative models can be used for motion planning and robot control by learning from prior data.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative models can assist in automating 3D modeling tasks, including generating 3D assets from text or images.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] World models are neural networks designed to learn representations of physical environments, including spatial and dynamic properties.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Recent multimodal systems have expanded these capabilities by integrating vision, language, and action into unified models.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI systems have been used in mathematics and computer science to generate candidate computer programs, proofs, constructions, or algorithms.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced FunSearch, a method for creating computer programs that solve mathematical and algorithmic problems.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] FunSearch was used to discover new mathematical constructions in the cap set problem and the bin packing problem.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaDev, which was used to discover small sorting algorithms that outperformed previously known human benchmarks and have been integrated into the LLVM standard C++ sorting library.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaEvolve, an AI system for general-purpose algorithm discovery and optimization.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] AlphaEvolve uses LLMs to propose code changes, automated evaluators to assess each candidate, and an evolutionary process to iteratively improve algorithms.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced GNoME, a method to propose candidate inorganic crystal structures for computational screening and experimental synthesis in material science.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Other material science methods include MatterGen, CDVAE, and CrystalFlow.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative engine optimization (GEO) is the practice of structuring digital content and managing online presence to improve visibility in responses generated by generative AI systems.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The practice influences the way large language models (LLMs) retrieve, summarize, and present information in response to user queries.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Related terms include answer engine optimization (AEO) and artificial intelligence optimization (AIO).
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI models are used to power chatbot products such as ChatGPT, programming tools such as GitHub Copilot, text-to-image products such as Midjourney, and text-to-video products such as Runway Gen-2.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI features have been integrated into a variety of existing commercially available products such as Microsoft Office (Microsoft Copilot), Google Photos, and the Adobe Suite (Adobe Firefly).
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many generative AI models are also available as open-source software, including Stable Diffusion and the LLaMA language model.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Smaller generative AI models with up to a few billion parameters can run on smartphones, embedded devices, and personal computers.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, LLaMA-7B (a version with 7 billion parameters) can run on a Raspberry Pi 4 and one version of Stable Diffusion can run on an iPhone 11.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Larger models with tens of billions of parameters can run on laptop or desktop computers.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] To achieve an acceptable speed, models of this size may require accelerators such as the GPU chips produced by NVIDIA and AMD or the Neural Engine included in Apple silicon products.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, the 65 billion parameter version of LLaMA can be configured to run on a desktop PC.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The advantages of running generative AI locally include protection of privacy and intellectual property, and avoidance of rate limiting and censorship.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The subreddit r/LocalLLaMA in particular focuses on using consumer-grade gaming graphics cards through such techniques as compression.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Language models with hundreds of billions of parameters, such as GPT-4 or PaLM, typically run on datacenter computers equipped with arrays of GPUs (such as NVIDIA's H100) or AI accelerator chips (such as Google's TPU).
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] These very large models are typically accessed as cloud services over the Internet.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2022, the United States New Export Controls on Advanced Computing and Semiconductors to China imposed restrictions on exports to China of GPU and AI accelerator chips used for generative AI.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Chips such as the NVIDIA A800 and the Biren Technology BR104 were developed to meet the requirements of the sanctions.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] There is free software on the market capable of recognizing text generated by generative artificial intelligence (such as GPTZero), as well as images, audio or video coming from it.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Potential mitigation strategies for detecting generative AI content include digital watermarking, content authentication, information retrieval, and machine learning classifier models.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Despite claims of accuracy, both free and paid AI text detectors have frequently produced false positives, mistakenly accusing students of submitting AI-generated work.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative adversarial networks (GANs) are a generative modeling technique which consist of two neural networks—the generator and the discriminator—trained simultaneously in a competitive setting.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The generator creates synthetic data by transforming random noise into samples that resemble the training dataset.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The discriminator is trained to distinguish the authentic data from synthetic data produced by the generator.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The two models engage in a minimax game: the generator aims to create increasingly realistic data to "fool" the discriminator, while the discriminator improves its ability to distinguish real from fake data.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] This continuous training setup enables the generator to produce high-quality and realistic outputs.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Variational autoencoders (VAEs) are deep learning models that probabilistically encode data.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] They are typically used for tasks such as noise reduction from images, data compression, identifying unusual patterns, and facial recognition.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Unlike standard autoencoders, which compress input data into a fixed latent representation, VAEs model the latent space as a probability distribution, allowing for smooth sampling and interpolation between data points.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The encoder ("recognition model") maps input data to a latent space, producing means and variances that define a probability distribution.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The decoder ("generative model") samples from this latent distribution and attempts to reconstruct the original input.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Transformers became the foundation for the generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) series developed by OpenAI, replacing traditional recurrent and convolutional models.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The self-attention mechanism enables the model to determine the relative importance of each token in a sequence when predicting the next token, thereby improving contextual understanding.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Unlike recurrent neural networks, transformers process tokens in parallel, which improves training efficiency and scalability.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the United States, a group of companies including OpenAI, Alphabet, and Meta signed a voluntary agreement with the Biden administration in July 2023 to watermark AI-generated content.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In October 2023, Executive Order 14110 applied the Defense Production Act to require all US companies to report information to the federal government when training certain high-impact AI models.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the European Union (EU), the Artificial Intelligence Act includes requirements to disclose copyrighted material used to train generative AI systems, and to label any AI-generated output as such.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In China, the Interim Measures for the Management of Generative AI Services introduced by the Cyberspace Administration of China regulates any public-facing generative AI.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] It includes requirements to watermark generated images or videos, regulations on training data and label quality, restrictions on personal data collection, and a guideline that generative AI services must "adhere to socialist core values".
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI systems such as ChatGPT and Midjourney are trained on large, publicly available datasets that include copyrighted works.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI developers have argued that such training is protected under fair use, while copyright holders have argued that it infringes their rights.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Proponents of fair use training have argued that it is a transformative use and does not involve making copies of copyrighted works available to the public.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Critics have argued that image generators such as Midjourney can create nearly-identical copies of some copyrighted images, and that generative AI programs compete with the content they are trained on.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] As of 2024, several lawsuits related to the use of copyrighted material in training are ongoing.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Getty Images has sued Stability AI over the use of its images to train Stable Diffusion.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Both the Authors Guild and The New York Times have sued Microsoft and OpenAI over the use of their works to train ChatGPT.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] A separate question is whether AI-generated works can qualify for copyright protection.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The United States Copyright Office has ruled that works created by artificial intelligence without any human input cannot be copyrighted, because they lack human authorship.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Some legal professionals have suggested that *Naruto v.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] 9th Circuit Court of Appeals held that non-humans cannot be copyright holders of artistic works, could be a potential precedent in copyright litigation over works created by generative AI.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, the office has also begun taking public input to determine if these rules need to be refined for generative AI.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Whether such modifications rise to the minimum standard of originality required under Feist will depend on a case-by-case determination.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In those cases where they do, the output should be copyrightable" Subsequently, the USCO registered the first visual artwork to be composed of entirely AI-generated materials, titled "A Single Piece of American Cheese".
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The development of generative AI has raised concerns from governments, businesses, and individuals, resulting in protests, legal actions, calls to pause AI experiments, and actions by multiple governments.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In addition, generative AI has a significant carbon footprint.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] A study presented in the 2026 Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems found that overreliance on generative AI can decrease one's ability to discern misinformation, the study tracked participants, mostly from the UK and US, for a period of 4 weeks.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to generate and modify academic prose, paraphrase sources, and translate languages.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The use of generative AI in a classroom setting has challenged traditional definitions of academic plagiarism, leading to a "cat-and-mouse" dynamic between students using AI and institutions attempting to detect it.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the immediate wake of ChatGPT's release, many school districts and universities issued temporary bans on the technology, though many institutions have since moved toward policies of managed integration.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, the implementation of these policies often lacks clarity.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Research suggests that the burden of interpreting "acceptable use" frequently falls on individual students and teachers, creating an environment where academic honesty becomes difficult to define and enforce.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] A commonly proposed use for teachers is grading and giving feedback.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies like Pearson and ETS use AI to score grammar, mechanics, usage, and style, but not for main ideas or overall structure.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The National Council of Teachers of English stated that machine scoring makes students feel their writing is not worth reading.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI scoring has also given unfair results for students from different ethnic backgrounds.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In April 2023, it was reported that image generation AI has resulted in 70% of the jobs for video game illustrators in China being lost.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In July 2023, developments in generative AI contributed to the 2023 Hollywood labor disputes.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Fran Drescher, president of the Screen Actors Guild, declared that "artificial intelligence poses an existential threat to creative professions" during the 2023 SAG-AFTRA strike.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Voice generation AI has been seen as a potential challenge to the voice acting sector.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, a 2025 study concluded that the US labor market had so far not experienced a discernible disruption from generative AI.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Another study reported that Danish workers who used chatbots saved 2.8% of their time on average, and found no significant change in earnings or hours worked.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In January 2023, *Futurism* broke the story that CNET had been using an undisclosed internal AI tool to write at least 77 of its stories; after the news broke, CNET posted corrections to 41 of the stories.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In April 2023, *Die Aktuelle* published an AI-generated fake interview of Michael Schumacher.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In May 2024, *Futurism* noted that a content management system video by AdVon Commerce, which had used generative AI to produce articles for many of the aforementioned outlets, appeared to show that they "had produced tens of thousands of articles for more than 150 publishers".
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, a report from the American Sunlight Project stated that Pravda network was publishing as many as 10,000 articles a day, and concluded that much of this content aimed to push Russian narratives into large language models through their training data.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In June 2024, Reuters Institute published its *Digital News Report for 2024*.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In a survey of people in America and Europe, Reuters Institute reports that 52% and 47% respectively are uncomfortable with news produced by "mostly AI with some human oversight", and 23% and 15% respectively report being comfortable.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] 42% of Americans and 33% of Europeans reported that they were comfortable with news produced by "mainly human with some help from AI".
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The results of global surveys reported that people were more uncomfortable with news topics including politics (46%), crime (43%), and local news (37%) produced by AI than other news topics.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2025 Pew Research Survey found roughly half of all U.S. adults say that AI will have a very (24%) or somewhat (26%) negative impact on the news people get in the U.S. over the next 20 years.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] A language model may associate certain professions with specific genders if such patterns are prevalent in the data.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Similarly, image generation systems prompted with terms such as "a photo of a CEO" have been observed to disproportionately generate images of white male individuals when trained on biased datasets.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI software, when using voice recognition software in particular, struggles to recognize and understand speech impediments.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, people with a stutter struggle to activate voice-activated assistants such as Gemini and Siri due to how the software was trained.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies that use AI systems to hire for new positions also filter out people with accents and speech due to voice recognition software incorrectly transcribing how candidates speak during the interview process.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Because of this, people with disabilities and uncommon accents don't often make it to a human interviewer when these generative AI systems are used.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] This is due to many AI models being trained and produced in the United States, and therefore, off of American accents.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfakes (a portmanteau of "deep learning" and "fake") are AI-generated media that take a person in an existing image or video and replace them with someone else's likeness using artificial neural networks.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfakes have garnered widespread attention and concerns for their uses in deepfake celebrity pornographic videos, revenge porn, fake news, hoaxes, health disinformation, financial fraud, and covert foreign election interference.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Instances of users abusing software to generate controversial statements in the vocal style of celebrities, public officials, and other famous individuals have raised ethical concerns over voice generation AI.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In response, companies such as ElevenLabs have stated that they would work on mitigating potential abuse through safeguards and identity verification.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Concerns and fandoms have spawned from AI-generated music.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The same software used to clone voices has been used on famous musicians' voices to create songs that mimic their voices, gaining both tremendous popularity and criticism.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Similar techniques have also been used to create improved quality or full-length versions of songs that have been leaked or have yet to be released.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI has been noted for its use by state-sponsored propaganda campaigns in information laundering.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to a 2025 report by Graphika, generative AI is used to launder articles from Chinese state media such as China Global Television Network through various social media sites in an attempt to disguise the articles' origin.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] A paper published by researchers at Amazon Web Services AI Labs found that over 57% of sentences from a sample of over 6 billion sentences from Common Crawl, a snapshot of web pages, were machine translated.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many of these automated translations were seen as lower quality, especially for sentences that were translated into at least three languages.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Wolof, Xhosa) were translated across more languages than higher-resource languages (ex.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The adoption of generative AI tools led to an explosion of AI-generated content across multiple domains.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] A study from University College London estimated that in 2023, more than 60,000 scholarly articles—over 1% of all publications—were likely written with LLM assistance.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to Stanford University's Institute for Human-Centered AI, approximately 17.5% of newly published computer science papers and 16.9% of peer review text now incorporate content generated by LLMs.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] If AI-generated content is included in new data crawls from the Internet for additional training of AI models, defects in the resulting models may occur.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Training an AI model exclusively on the output of another AI model produces a lower-quality model.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Repeating this process, where each new model is trained on the previous model's output, leads to progressive degradation and eventually results in a "model collapse" after multiple iterations.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] On the other side, synthetic data can be deployed to train machine learning models while preserving user privacy.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The approach is not limited to text generation; image generation has been employed to train computer vision models.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many websites that allow explicit AI generated images or videos have been created, and this has been used to create illegal content, such as rape, child sexual abuse material, necrophilia, and zoophilia.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI's ability to create realistic fake content has been exploited in numerous types of cybercrime, including phishing scams.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfake video and audio have been used to create disinformation and fraud.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2020, former Google click fraud czar Shuman Ghosemajumder argued that once deepfake videos become perfectly realistic, they would stop appearing remarkable to viewers, potentially leading to uncritical acceptance of false information.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Additionally, large language models and other forms of text-generation AI have been used to create fake reviews of e-commerce websites to boost ratings.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Cybercriminals have created large language models focused on fraud, including WormGPT and FraudGPT.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2023 study showed that generative AI can be vulnerable to jailbreaks, reverse psychology and prompt injection attacks, enabling attackers to obtain help with harmful requests, such as for crafting social engineering and phishing attacks.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Additionally, other researchers have demonstrated that open-source models can be fine-tuned to remove their safety restrictions at low cost.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, Israel signed a $6 million contract with the US-based firm Clock Tower X that aimed to influence ChatGPT, Gemini and Grok by spreading pro-Israel information onto social media and websites.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] This was in an attempt to take advantage of the retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) technique which is used by LLMs to provide more up-to-date information.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from covered service providers, including some AI service providers, regardless of where the data is physically stored.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Courts can require parent companies to provide data held by their subsidiaries, and such orders may be accompanied by nondisclosure requirements preventing the provider from notifying affected users.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] This framework has been described in legal commentary as creating legal tension with Article 48 of the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] As a result, service providers operating in both jurisdictions may face competing legal obligations under U.S. and EU law.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI has a significant carbon footprint due to growing energy consumption from both training and usage.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] There is also concern that these impacts may increase as these models are incorporated into widely used search engines such as Google Search and Bing, as chatbots and other applications become more popular, and as models need to be retrained.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Training frontier AI models requires an enormous amount of computing power.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Usually only Big Tech companies have the financial resources to make such investments.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Smaller start-ups such as Cohere and OpenAI end up buying access to data centers from Google and Microsoft respectively.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Tools such as GPTZero can detect content generated by AI.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, they can also make false accusations (false positives).
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] Digital watermarking is a technique that improves detection accuracy.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] It works by altering the generated content at the source, in subtle ways which can be detected by corresponding software.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, OpenAI developed a watermarking tool for ChatGPT.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] They didn't release it, because they worried that users would switch to competitors.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] They also argued that it would be easy to circumvent, for example by asking another AI to rephrase.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In March 2025, the Cyberspace Administration of China issued rules, requiring online service providers to label AI content.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In May 2025, Google deployed its watermarking tool, SynthID.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] It marks output from Gemini (text), Imagen (images), and Veo (video).
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] To detect output from these products, one uses Google's "SynthID detector" portal.
[src:stable-diffusion/generative-artificial-intelligence] In June 2025, users mistakenly accused gaming companies of using generative AI for the video games *Little Droid* and *Catly*.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] A **latent space**, also known as a **latent feature space** or **embedding space**, is an embedding of a set of items within a manifold in which items resembling each other are positioned closer to one another.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] Position within the latent space can be viewed as being defined by a set of latent variables that emerge from the resemblances between the objects.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] In most cases, the dimensionality of the latent space is chosen to be lower than the dimensionality of the feature space from which the data points are drawn, making the construction of a latent space an example of dimensionality reduction, which can also be viewed as a form of data compression.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] Latent spaces are usually fit via machine learning, and they can then be used as feature spaces in machine learning models, including classifiers and other supervised predictors.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] The interpretation of latent spaces in machine learning models is an ongoing area of research, but achieving clear interpretations remains challenging.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] The black-box nature of these models often makes the latent space unintuitive, while its high-dimensional, complex, and nonlinear characteristics further complicate the task of understanding it.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] Analysis of the latent space geometry of diffusion models reveals a fractal structure of phase transitions in the latent space, characterized by abrupt changes in the Fisher information metric.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] Some visualization techniques have been developed to connect the latent space to the visual world, but there is often not a direct connection between the latent space interpretation and the model itself.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] Such techniques include t-distributed stochastic neighbor embedding (t-SNE), where the latent space is mapped to two dimensions for visualization.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] Latent space distances lack physical units, so the interpretation of these distances may depend on the application.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] Several embedding models have been developed to perform this transformation to create latent space embeddings given a set of data items and a similarity function.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] These models learn the embeddings by leveraging statistical techniques and machine learning algorithms.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] GloVe: GloVe (Global Vectors for Word Representation) is another widely used embedding model for NLP.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] It combines global statistical information from a corpus with local context information to learn word embeddings.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] GloVe embeddings are known for capturing both semantic and relational similarities between words.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] Siamese Networks: Siamese networks are a type of neural network architecture commonly used for similarity-based embedding.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] They consist of two identical subnetworks that process two input samples and produce their respective embeddings.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] Siamese networks are often used for tasks like image similarity, recommendation systems, and face recognition.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] Variational Autoencoders (VAEs): VAEs are generative models that simultaneously learn to encode and decode data.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] The latent space in VAEs acts as an embedding space.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] By training VAEs on high-dimensional data, such as images or audio, the model learns to encode the data into a compact latent representation.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] VAEs are known for their ability to generate new data samples from the learned latent space.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] Multimodality refers to the integration and analysis of multiple modes or types of data within a single model or framework.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] Embedding multimodal data involves capturing relationships and interactions between different data types, such as images, text, audio, and structured data.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] Multimodal embedding models aim to learn joint representations that fuse information from multiple modalities, allowing for cross-modal analysis and tasks.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] These models enable applications like image captioning, visual question answering, and multimodal sentiment analysis.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] To embed multimodal data, specialized architectures such as deep multimodal networks or multimodal transformers are employed.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] These architectures combine different types of neural network modules to process and integrate information from various modalities.
[src:stable-diffusion/latent-space] The resulting embeddings capture the complex relationships between different data types, facilitating multimodal analysis and understanding.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] It is primarily used to generate detailed images conditioned on text descriptions, though it can also be applied to other tasks such as inpainting, outpainting, and generating image-to-image translations guided by a text prompt.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Its development involved researchers from the CompVis Group at LMU Munich and Runway with a computational donation from Stability and training data from non-profit organizations.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Stable Diffusion is a latent diffusion model, a kind of deep generative artificial neural network.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Its code and model weights have been released publicly, and an optimized version can run on most consumer hardware equipped with a modest GPU with as little as 2.4 GB VRAM.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] This marked a departure from previous proprietary text-to-image models such as DALL-E and Midjourney which were accessible only via cloud services.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Stable Diffusion originated from a project called **Latent Diffusion**, developed in Germany by researchers at LMU Munich in Munich and Heidelberg University.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Four of the original 5 authors (Robin Rombach, Andreas Blattmann, Patrick Esser and Dominik Lorenz) later joined Stability AI and released subsequent versions of Stable Diffusion.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The technical license for the model was released by the CompVis group at LMU Munich.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Development was led by Patrick Esser of Runway and Robin Rombach of CompVis, who were among the researchers who had earlier invented the latent diffusion model architecture used by Stable Diffusion.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Stability AI also credited EleutherAI and LAION (a German nonprofit which assembled the dataset on which Stable Diffusion was trained) as supporters of the project.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Diffusion models, introduced in 2015, are trained with the objective of removing successive applications of Gaussian noise on training images, which can be thought of as a sequence of denoising autoencoders.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The name *diffusion* is from the thermodynamic diffusion, since they were first developed with inspiration from thermodynamics.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Models in Stable Diffusion series before SD 3 all used a variant of diffusion models, called latent diffusion model (LDM), developed in 2021 by the CompVis (Computer Vision & Learning) group at LMU Munich.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Stable Diffusion consists of 3 parts: the variational autoencoder (VAE), U-Net, and an optional text encoder.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The VAE encoder compresses the image from pixel space to a smaller dimensional latent space, capturing a more fundamental semantic meaning of the image.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Gaussian noise is iteratively applied to the compressed latent representation during forward diffusion.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The U-Net block, composed of a ResNet backbone, denoises the output from forward diffusion backwards to obtain a latent representation.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Finally, the VAE decoder generates the final image by converting the representation back into pixel space.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The denoising step can be flexibly conditioned on a string of text, an image, or another modality.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The encoded conditioning data is exposed to denoising U-Nets via a cross-attention mechanism.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] For conditioning on text, the fixed, pretrained CLIP ViT-L/14 text encoder is used to transform text prompts to an embedding space.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Researchers point to increased computational efficiency for training and generation as an advantage of LDMs.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] With 860 million parameters in the U-Net and 123 million in the text encoder, Stable Diffusion is considered relatively lightweight by 2022 standards, and unlike other diffusion models, it can run on consumer GPUs, and even CPU-only if using the OpenVINO version of Stable Diffusion.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The XL version uses the same LDM architecture as previous versions, except larger: larger UNet backbone, larger cross-attention context, two text encoders instead of one, and trained on multiple aspect ratios (not just the square aspect ratio like previous versions).
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The SD XL Refiner, released at the same time, has the same architecture as SD XL, but it was trained for adding fine details to preexisting images via text-conditional img2img.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The 3.0 version completely changes the backbone.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Not a UNet, but a *Rectified Flow Transformer*, which implements the rectified flow method with a Transformer.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The Transformer architecture used for SD 3.0 has three "tracks", for original text encoding, transformed text encoding, and image encoding (in latent space).
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The transformed text encoding and image encoding are mixed during each transformer block.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The architecture is named "multimodal diffusion transformer (MMDiT), where the "multimodal" means that it mixes text and image encodings inside its operations.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] This differs from previous versions of DiT, where the text encoding affects the image encoding, but not vice versa.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The dataset was created by LAION, a German non-profit which receives funding from Stability AI.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The Stable Diffusion model was trained on three subsets of LAION-5B: laion2B-en, laion-high-resolution, and laion-aesthetics v2 5+.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] An investigation by Bayerischer Rundfunk showed that LAION's datasets, hosted on Hugging Face, contain large amounts of private and sensitive data.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The LAION-Aesthetics v2 5+ subset also excluded low-resolution images and images which LAION-5B-WatermarkDetection identified as carrying a watermark with greater than 80% probability.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Final rounds of training additionally dropped 10% of text conditioning to improve Classifier-Free Diffusion Guidance.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The model was trained using 256 Nvidia A100 GPUs on Amazon Web Services for a total of 150,000 GPU-hours, at a cost of $600,000.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Stable Diffusion has issues with degradation and inaccuracies in certain scenarios.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Another challenge is in generating human limbs due to poor data quality of limbs in the LAION database.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The model is insufficiently trained to replicate human limbs and faces due to the lack of representative features in the database, and prompting the model to generate images of such type can confound the model.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] In addition to human limbs, Stable Diffusion is unable to generate legible ambigrams and some other forms of text and typography.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Stable Diffusion XL (SDXL) version 1.0, released in July 2023, introduced native 1024x1024 resolution and improved generation for limbs and text.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Accessibility for individual developers can also be a problem.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] In order to customize the model for new use cases that are not included in the dataset, such as generating anime characters ("waifu diffusion"), new data and further training are required.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Fine-tuned adaptations of Stable Diffusion created through additional retraining have been used for a variety of different use-cases, from medical imaging to algorithmically generated music.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] However, this fine-tuning process is sensitive to the quality of new data; low resolution images or different resolutions from the original data can not only fail to learn the new task but degrade the overall performance of the model.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Even when the model is additionally trained on high quality images, it is difficult for individuals to run models in consumer electronics.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] For example, the training process for waifu-diffusion requires a minimum 30 GB of VRAM, which exceeds the usual resource provided in such consumer GPUs as Nvidia's GeForce 30 series, which has only about 12 GB.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The creators of Stable Diffusion acknowledge the potential for algorithmic bias, as the model was primarily trained on images with English descriptions.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] As a result, generated images reinforce social biases and are from a western perspective, as the creators note that the model lacks data from other communities and cultures.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The model gives more accurate results for prompts that are written in English in comparison to those written in other languages, with western or white cultures often being the default representation.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] To address the limitations of the model's initial training, end-users may opt to implement additional training to fine-tune generation outputs to match more specific use-cases, a process also referred to as personalization.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The Stable Diffusion model supports the ability to generate new images from scratch through the use of a text prompt describing elements to be included or omitted from the output.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Existing images can be re-drawn by the model to incorporate new elements described by a text prompt (a process known as "guided image synthesis") through its diffusion-denoising mechanism.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] In addition, the model also allows the use of prompts to partially alter existing images via inpainting and outpainting, when used with an appropriate user interface that supports such features, of which numerous different open source implementations exist.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Stable Diffusion is recommended to be run with 10 GB or more VRAM, however users with less VRAM may opt to load the weights in float16 precision instead of the default float32 to tradeoff model performance with lower VRAM usage.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The text to image sampling script within Stable Diffusion, known as "txt2img", consumes a text prompt in addition to assorted option parameters covering sampling types, output image dimensions, and seed values.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The script outputs an image file based on the model's interpretation of the prompt.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Generated images are tagged with an invisible digital watermark to allow users to identify an image as generated by Stable Diffusion, although this watermark loses its efficacy if the image is resized or rotated.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Each txt2img generation will involve a specific seed value which affects the output image.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Users may opt to randomize the seed in order to explore different generated outputs, or use the same seed to obtain the same image output as a previously generated image.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Users are also able to adjust the number of inference steps for the sampler; a higher value takes a longer duration of time, however a smaller value may result in visual defects.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Another configurable option, the classifier-free guidance scale value, allows the user to adjust how closely the output image adheres to the prompt.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] More experimentative use cases may opt for a lower scale value, while use cases aiming for more specific outputs may use a higher value.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Additional text2img features are provided by front-end implementations of Stable Diffusion, which allow users to modify the weight given to specific parts of the text prompt.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Emphasis markers allow users to add or reduce emphasis to keywords by enclosing them with brackets.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] An alternative method of adjusting weight to parts of the prompt are "negative prompts".
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Negative prompts are a feature included in some front-end implementations, including Stability AI's own DreamStudio cloud service, and allow the user to specify prompts which the model should avoid during image generation.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The specified prompts may be undesirable image features that would otherwise be present within image outputs due to the positive prompts provided by the user, or due to how the model was originally trained, with mangled human hands being a common example.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Stable Diffusion also includes another sampling script, "img2img", which consumes a text prompt, path to an existing image, and strength value between 0.0 and 1.0.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The script outputs a new image based on the original image that also features elements provided within the text prompt.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The strength value denotes the amount of noise added to the output image.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] A higher strength value produces more variation within the image but may produce an image that is not semantically consistent with the prompt provided.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] There are different methods for performing img2img.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The main method is SDEdit, which first adds noise to an image, then denoises it as usual in text2img.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The ability of img2img to add noise to the original image makes it potentially useful for data anonymization and data augmentation, in which the visual features of image data are changed and anonymized.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The same process may also be useful for image upscaling, in which the resolution of an image is increased, with more detail potentially being added to the image.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Additionally, Stable Diffusion has been experimented with as a tool for image compression.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Compared to JPEG and WebP, the recent methods used for image compression in Stable Diffusion face limitations in preserving small text and faces.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Additional use-cases for image modification via img2img are offered by numerous front-end implementations of the Stable Diffusion model.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Inpainting involves selectively modifying a portion of an existing image delineated by a user-provided layer mask, which fills the masked space with newly generated content based on the provided prompt.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] A dedicated model specifically fine-tuned for inpainting use-cases was created by Stability AI alongside the release of Stable Diffusion 2.0.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Conversely, outpainting extends an image beyond its original dimensions, filling the previously empty space with content generated based on the provided prompt.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] ControlNet is a neural network architecture designed to manage diffusion models by incorporating additional conditions.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] It duplicates the weights of neural network blocks into a "locked" copy and a "trainable" copy.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The "trainable" copy learns the desired condition, while the "locked" copy preserves the original model.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] This approach ensures that training with small datasets of image pairs does not compromise the integrity of production-ready diffusion models.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The "zero convolution" is a 1×1 convolution with both weight and bias initialized to zero.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Before training, all zero convolutions produce zero output, preventing any distortion caused by ControlNet.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] No layer is trained from scratch; the process is still fine-tuning, keeping the original model secure.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] This method enables training on small-scale or even personal devices.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] ControlNet is commonly used to alter the generation of an image based on an input image that maps properties desired in the final image.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Common mapping image types include a depth map, edges, or one or more skeletal poses.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] These inputs may be generated directly, but they are often derived from still other images, using neural nets or processes like edge detection.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Stability provides an online image generation service called *DreamStudio*.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The company also released an open source version of *DreamStudio* called *StableStudio*.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Stable Diffusion 3.5 Large was made available for enterprise usage on Amazon Bedrock of Amazon Web Services.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Stable Diffusion claims no rights on generated images and freely gives users the rights of usage to any generated images from the model provided that the image content is not illegal or harmful to individuals.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The images Stable Diffusion was trained on have been filtered without human input, leading to some harmful images and large amounts of private and sensitive information appearing in the training data.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] More traditional visual artists have expressed concern that widespread usage of image synthesis software such as Stable Diffusion may eventually lead to human artists, along with photographers, models, cinematographers, and actors, gradually losing commercial viability against AI-based competitors.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Stable Diffusion is notably more permissive in the types of content users may generate, such as violent or sexually explicit imagery, in comparison to other commercial products based on generative AI.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] In addition, Mostaque argues that the intention behind the open availability of Stable Diffusion is to end corporate control and dominance over such technologies, who have previously only developed closed AI systems for image synthesis.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] This is reflected by the fact that any restrictions Stability AI places on the content that users may generate can easily be bypassed due to the availability of the source code.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Controversy around photorealistic sexualized depictions of underage characters have been brought up, due to such images generated by Stable Diffusion being shared on websites such as Pixiv.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] In June of 2024, a hack on an extension of ComfyUI, a user interface for Stable Diffusion, took place, with the hackers claiming they targeted users who committed "one of our sins", which included AI-art generation, art theft, promoting cryptocurrency.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] District Judge William Orrick inclined to dismiss most of the lawsuit filed by Andersen, McKernan, and Ortiz but allowed them to file a new complaint, providing them an opportunity to reframe their arguments.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] In January 2023, Getty Images initiated legal proceedings against Stability AI in the English High Court, alleging significant infringement of its intellectual property rights.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Getty Images claims that Stability AI "scraped" millions of images from Getty’s websites without consent and used these images to train and develop its deep-learning Stable Diffusion model.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] As of November 4, 2025 Getty Images largely lost the lawsuit over AI image generator to Stability AI, prompting Getty and some lawyers to call for stronger protections for copyright owners in Britain.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Unlike models like DALL-E, Stable Diffusion makes its source code available, along with the model (pretrained weights).
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Prior to Stable Diffusion 3, it applied the Creative ML OpenRAIL-M license, a form of Responsible AI License (RAIL), to the model (M).
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] The user owns the rights to their generated output images, and is free to use them commercially.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] Stable Diffusion 3.5 applies the permissive Stability AI Community License while commercial enterprises with revenue exceed $1 million need the Stability AI Enterprise License.
[src:stable-diffusion/stable-diffusion] As with the OpenRAIL-M license, the user retains the rights to their generated output images and is free to use them commercially.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] A **text-to-image** (**T2I** or **TTI**) **model** is a machine learning model which takes an input natural language prompt and produces an image matching that description.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Text-to-image models gradually began to be developed in the mid-2010s during the beginnings of the AI boom, as a result of advances in deep neural networks.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] In 2022, the output of state-of-the-art text-to-image models—such as OpenAI's DALL-E 2, Google Brain's Imagen, Stability AI's Stable Diffusion, Midjourney, and Runway's Gen-4—began to be considered to approach the quality of real photographs and human-drawn art.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Text-to-image models are generally latent diffusion models, which perform the diffusion process in a compressed latent space rather than directly in pixel space.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] An autoencoder (often a variational autoencoder (VAE)) is used to convert between pixel space and this latent representation.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] These systems typically use a pretrained language or vision–language model to convert the input prompt into a text embedding, and a diffusion-based generative image model that produces images conditioned on that embedding.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] The most effective models have generally been trained on massive amounts of image and text data scraped from the web.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Before the rise of deep learning in the 2010s, attempts to build text-to-image models were limited to collages by arranging existing component images, such as from a database of clip art.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] The inverse task, image captioning, was more tractable, and a number of image captioning deep learning models came prior to the first text-to-image models.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] The first modern text-to-image model, alignDRAW, was introduced in 2015 by researchers from the University of Toronto. alignDRAW extended the previously-introduced DRAW architecture (which used a recurrent variational autoencoder with an attention mechanism) to be conditioned on text sequences.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Images generated by alignDRAW were in small resolution (32×32 pixels, attained from resizing) and were considered to be 'low in diversity'.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] The model was able to generalize to objects not represented in the training data (such as a red school bus) and appropriately handled novel prompts such as "a stop sign is flying in blue skies", exhibiting output that it was not merely "memorizing" data from the training set.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] In 2016, Reed, Akata, Yan et al. became the first to use generative adversarial networks for the text-to-image task.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] With models trained on narrow, domain-specific datasets, they were able to generate "visually plausible" images of birds and flowers from text captions like *"an all black bird with a distinct thick, rounded bill"*.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] A model trained on the more diverse COCO (Common Objects in Context) dataset produced images which were "from a distance... encouraging", but which lacked coherence in their details.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Later systems include VQGAN-CLIP, XMC-GAN, and GauGAN2.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] One of the first text-to-image models to capture widespread public attention was OpenAI's DALL-E, a transformer system announced in January 2021.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] A successor capable of generating more complex and realistic images, DALL-E 2, was unveiled in April 2022, followed by Stable Diffusion that was publicly released in August 2022.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] In August 2022, text-to-image personalization allows to teach the model a new concept using a small set of images of a new object that was not included in the training set of the text-to-image foundation model.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] This is achieved by textual inversion, namely, finding a new text term that correspond to these images.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Additional text-to-image models appeared with Adobe in March 2023 and Black Forest Labs in August 2024.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Following other text-to-image models, language model-powered text-to-video platforms such as Runway, Make-A-Video, Imagen Video, Midjourney, and Phenaki can generate video from text and/or text/image prompts.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Text-to-image models have been built using a variety of architectures.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] The text encoding step may be performed with a recurrent neural network such as a long short-term memory (LSTM) network, though transformer models have since become a more popular option.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] For the image generation step, conditional generative adversarial networks (GANs) was once widely used in early days.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Since 2020, diffusion models have become the popular option.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Rather than directly training a model to output a high-resolution image conditioned on a text embedding, a popular technique is to train a model to generate low-resolution images or latent space, and use one or more auxiliary deep learning models to upscale or decode it, filling in finer details.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Text-to-image models are trained on large datasets of (text, image) pairs, often scraped from the web.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] With their 2022 Imagen model, Google Brain reported positive results from using a large language model trained separately on a text-only corpus (with its weights subsequently frozen), a departure from the theretofore standard approach.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Training a text-to-image model requires a dataset of images paired with text captions.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] One dataset commonly used for this purpose is the COCO dataset.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Released by Microsoft in 2014, COCO consists of around 123,000 images depicting a diversity of objects with five captions per image, generated by human annotators.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Originally, the main focus of COCO was on the recognition of objects and scenes in images.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Oxford-120 Flowers and CUB-200 Birds are smaller datasets of around 10,000 images each, restricted to flowers and birds, respectively.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] It is considered less difficult to train a high-quality text-to-image model with these datasets because of their narrow range of subject matter.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] One of the largest open datasets for training text-to-image models is LAION-5B, containing more than 5 billion image-text pairs.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] This dataset was created using web scraping and automatic filtering based on similarity to high-quality artwork and professional photographs.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Because of this, however, it also contains controversial content, which has led to discussions about the ethics of its use.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Some modern AI platforms not only generate images from text but also create synthetic datasets to improve model training and fine-tuning.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] These datasets help avoid copyright issues and expand the diversity of training data.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Evaluating and comparing the quality of text-to-image models is a problem involving assessing multiple desirable properties.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] A desideratum specific to text-to-image models is that generated images semantically align with the text captions used to generate them.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] A number of schemes have been devised for assessing these qualities, some automated and others based on human judgement.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] A common algorithmic metric for assessing image quality and diversity is the Inception Score (IS), which is based on the distribution of labels predicted by a pretrained Inceptionv3 image classification model when applied to a sample of images generated by the text-to-image model.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] The score is increased when the image classification model predicts a single label with high probability, a scheme intended to favour "distinct" generated images.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Another popular metric is the related Fréchet inception distance, which compares the distribution of generated images and real training images according to features extracted by one of the final layers of a pretrained image classification model.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Generated images are sometimes used as sketches, low-cost experiments, inspiration, or illustrations of proof-of-concept-stage ideas.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] Additional functionalities or improvements may also relate to post-generation manual editing (i.e., polishing), such as subsequent tweaking with an image editor.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] In physical domains, concerns regarding structural integrity, material constraints, and cultural "ethno-computation" often limit AI to a "complementary enhancement" role rather than a substitute for production.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] This license can be used by individuals and organizations up to $1 million in revenue, for organizations with annual revenue more than $1 million, Stability AI Enterprise License is needed.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] All outputs are retained by users regardless of revenue.
[src:stable-diffusion/text-to-image-model] For the Schnell model, the Dev model is using a non-commercial license while the Pro model is proprietary (only available as API).
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] The U-Net architecture has also been employed in diffusion models for iterative image denoising.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] This technology underlies many modern image generation models, such as DALL-E, Midjourney, and Stable Diffusion.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] U-Net is also being explored for language models.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] Tokenization is not a separate step, allowing the model to more easily understand spelling and concurrently vectorizing / tokenizing higher level concepts.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] The U-Net architecture stems from the so-called "fully convolutional network".
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] The main idea is to supplement a usual contracting network by successive layers, where pooling operations are replaced by upsampling operators.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] Hence these layers increase the resolution of the output.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] A successive convolutional layer can then learn to assemble a precise output based on this information.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] One important modification in U-Net is that there are a large number of feature channels in the upsampling part, which allow the network to propagate context information to higher resolution layers.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] As a consequence, the expansive path is more or less symmetric to the contracting part, and yields a u-shaped architecture.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] The network only uses the valid part of each convolution without any fully connected layers.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] To predict the pixels in the border region of the image, the missing context is extrapolated by mirroring the input image.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] This tiling strategy is important to apply the network to large images, since otherwise the resolution would be limited by the GPU memory.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] Recently, there had also been an interest in receptive field based U-Net models for medical image segmentation.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] The network consists of a contracting path and an expansive path, which gives it the u-shaped architecture.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] The contracting path is a typical convolutional network that consists of repeated application of convolutions, each followed by a rectified linear unit (ReLU) and a max pooling operation.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] During the contraction, the spatial information is reduced while feature information is increased.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] The expansive pathway combines the feature and spatial information through a sequence of up-convolutions and concatenations with high-resolution features from the contracting path.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] There are many applications of U-Net in biomedical image segmentation, such as brain image segmentation (''BRATS'') and liver image segmentation ("siliver07") as well as protein binding site prediction.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] U-Net implementations have also found use in the physical sciences, for example in the analysis of micrographs of materials.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] Variations of the U-Net have also been applied for medical image reconstruction.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] TernausNet: U-Net with VGG11 Encoder Pre-Trained on ImageNet for Image Segmentation.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] In binding site prediction of protein structure.
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] U-Net was created by Olaf Ronneberger, Philipp Fischer, Thomas Brox in 2015 and reported in the paper "U-Net: Convolutional Networks for Biomedical Image Segmentation".
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] It is an improvement and development of FCN: Evan Shelhamer, Jonathan Long, Trevor Darrell (2014).
[src:stable-diffusion/u-net] "Fully convolutional networks for semantic segmentation".
